# Rust Style

Follow the official [Rust Style Guide](https://doc.rust-lang.org/style-guide/index.html).
Formatting is delegated to **default rustfmt** — run `cargo fmt` before committing and do
not add a `rustfmt.toml`. CI enforces `cargo fmt --check` and
`cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings`.

## Layout (rustfmt defaults — don't fight them)

- Spaces only (never tabs), 4-space indent, 100-char max line width, no
  trailing whitespace.
- Block indent over visual indent; trailing comma on every multi-line list.
- String literals (e.g. long SQL) are not wrapped by rustfmt — break them into
  multi-line literals yourself so every line stays within 100 chars.

## Items & imports

- `use` statements come **before** `mod` declarations; both come before other items.
- Keep import groups separated by a blank line, version-sorted within each group
  (rustfmt sorts within a group but never creates or merges groups):

```rust
use serde::Deserialize;   // 1. external crates (std first if used)
use worker::*;

use crate::models::Task;   // 2. crate-internal
```

- In list imports, `self` comes first and globs/nested groups last:
  `use a::{self, b, c::*};` Prefer several one-line `use` statements over one
  multi-line list.

## Comments & attributes

- Prefer `//` line comments; write complete sentences (capital letter, ending
  period). Keep comment lines within ~80 characters.
- Use `///` outer doc comments for public items; place doc comments **above**
  attributes (`///` then `#[derive(...)]`).
- One attribute per line; exactly one `#[derive(...)]` per item.

## Types & signatures

- Prefer named-field structs once a tuple struct stops fitting on one line.
- Prefer unit structs (`struct Foo;`) over empty `struct Foo {}` / `struct Foo();`.
- Single-letter generic parameters; reach for a `where` clause instead of
  line-breaking a generics clause.

## Cargo.toml

- `[package]` first, with `name` then `version` at the top and `description` last.
- Version-sort keys inside every other section (e.g. `[dependencies]`).
- Bare keys, one space around `=`, inline tables/arrays only while they fit on
  one line, blank line between sections.
